{"0": "Reading can be a social activity.", "1": "Think of the people who belong to book groups.", "2": "They choose books to read and then meet to discuss them.", "3": "Now, the website BookCrossing.com turns the page on the traditional idea of a book group.", "4": "Members go on the site and register the books they own and would like to share.", "5": "BookCrossing provides an identification number to stick inside the book.", "6": "Then the person leaves it in a public place, hoping that the book will have an adventure, traveling far and wide with each new reader who finds it.", "7": "Bruce Pederson, the managing director of BookCrossing, says, \"The two things that change your life are the people you meet and books you read.", "8": "BookCrossing combines both.\"", "9": "Members leave books on park benches and buses, in train stations and coffee shops.", "10": "Whoever finds their book will go to the site and record where they found it.", "11": "People who find a book can also leave a journal entry describing what they thought of it.", "12": "E-mails are then sent to the BookCrossing to keep them updated about where their books have been found.", "13": "Bruce Peterson says the idea is for people not to be selfish by keeping a book to gather dust on a shelf at home.", "14": "BookCrossing is part of a trend among people who want to get back to the \"real\" and not the virtual.", "15": "The site now has more than one million members in more than one hundred thirty-five countries."}